I made this blog to talk about my passions. In particular, I’ll be
        diving into math, computer science, philosophy (maybe), and a few other random
        interests along the way. I’m excited to share my thoughts as I go and to make
        life easier to someone.

Tenses
Referring to the present
TenseFunctionExamplesNote
Present simpleRegular habitSomething always trueI see my friends at the weekend–
Present continuousA planA temporary situationWith always/foreverI’m seeing my friends at the weekendUsed with active verbs (not stative verbs, except those who calls back to an active verb, eg. having launch)
Present perfectSimple: To refer to the present result of a past action/eventTo refer to an event/action that happened at an unspecified time in a period up to nowTo focus on the number of times an action has been repeated Continuous: An action that started in the past and has continues until the presentI’ve written the article (It’s finished)I’ve been writing the article all morning (It probably isn’t finished)Simple: Focuses on a completed actionContinuous: Focuses on an ongoning action

Referring to the past
TenseFunctionExamplesNote
Past simplePast events/actions/habits, with a time referenceI always watched the TV news when I lived abroad–
Past continuousTo show a continued action which was happening when another action took placeTo refer to 2 actions happening at the same time in the pastThe magazine was launched just when the sales of news magazines were fallingWhile some journalists were discussing the latest developments, others were watching the breaking news online–
Past perfectTo show that an action happened earlier than another past actionI didn’t watch the programme about hurricanes on TV last night, because I’d already seen a similar programme–
Past perfect continuousTo refer to an action that happened during a period leading up to another past actionTo show how long an action continued until a certain point in the pastThe newspaper had been losing so much money that the owner decided to close it downThe reporters had been following the film star for days before they were able to interview her–
 Used to/Didn’t use to + InfinitiveWould + InfinitiveTo refer to repeated actions or habits in the past that are no longer the caseTo refer to a past state (not Would)Before digital cameras were invented, people used to take/would take photos on filmThis used to be (Would be) a very quiet neighbourhoodUsed to is not normally used with time expressions specifying the duration of the action: I used to live in Edinburgh before I moved to LondonI lived (Used to live) in Edinburgh for five years before I moved to London 

Referring to the future
TenseFunctionExamplesNote
Future simple (will + Infinitive)To predict the futureTo express a decision that has just been made (usually by the speaker)To express the speaker’s insistence on doing somethingAftershocks from yesterday’s earthquake will probably continue for several days I know! We’ll go to the Science MuseumWe will find somewhere better to live - I promise you–
Going to + InfinitiveFor decisions/intensions about the futureFor predictions about the future based on evidence, or to refer to the outcome of a process that has already startedThe owner of the local bookshop is going to invite a well-known author to give a talkYou drive much too fast. You’re going to have an accident one of these days–
Present continuousTo refer to something already arrangedWe’re meating the journalist tomorrow morning–
Present simpleFor future events fixed by a timetable or scheduleThe sun rises at 5.30 tomorrowThe next train is at 11 o’clock–
Future continuousFor temporary actions in progress at a particular time in the futureTo ask about the listener’s plans (often to lead on to a request) This time next week, we’ll be flying to BrazilWill you be going out this evening? If not, can I come around and see you?–
Future perfectFor actions in a period up to a particular time in the futureFor actions which will be completed before a particular time in the future The oil spill will have caused a lot of damage by the time the flow from the ship can be stoppedI’ll have finished lunch long before you arrive–
Future perfect continuousFor actions in a period up to a particular time in the future, emphasising the lenght of timeAt the beginning of next March, I’ll have been working in the same job for 17 years–


NOTE:  In time and conditional clauses referring to the future will is not normally used to refer to the future. Instead, present tenses (simple, continuous and perfect) are used.
